requirement description

Figure 1: Different cancers shown in different colors

https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1714448

fromhttps://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1714448

GOKEGG

Figure 2: Do similar diagrams for GO, KEGG enrichment analysis results show. Display non-significant results in gray, separate names on the left and right, with positive and negative enrichment separated, left and right separate drawn on a graph.

https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-018-0096-5

GSVA scoreGSVA

fromhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-018-0096-5

The input data for the original article is the GSVA score; this code only mimics the form and does not include GSVA analysis.

application scenario

GSVA

Scenario 1: Comparison of a certain index across tumors, such as tumor remission rate in Figure 1.

Scenario 2: GSVA results are presented, similar to Figure 2.

Scenario 1

ID

Each ID is shown as a color

Start drawing

library(ggplot2)
p<-ggplot(df,aes(x=index,y=score,fill=ID)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity',width = 0.8) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "Qualitative", palette = "Paired") + #bar color of bar
  
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(-100, 100, 10), #y y-axis scale
                     expand = c(0,0)) + # there's no space between the top and the bottom
  scale_x_discrete(expand = expand_scale(mult = c(0.01,0))) + # leave the left side blank, the right side goes to the end

  #3
  #draw 3 horizontal lines
  geom_hline(yintercept = c(-30,0,20), 
             linetype = 5, # draw a dotted line
             size = 0.3) + # thickness of line
  
  #
  #other themes
  labs(x = "", y = "Maximum Change in Tumor Size (%)", 
       title = "A Maximum Change in Tumor Size, According to Tumor Type") +
  theme_bw() + # remove background color
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + # remove gridlines
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) + # remove outer border
  theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "black")) + # display lines along the axes
  theme(axis.line.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks.x = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_blank()) + #x remove x-axis
  
  #
  #legend
  guides(fill = guide_legend(ncol = 5,title = NULL)) + #5 legend divided into 5 columns
  scale_size(range=c(5,20)) +
  theme(legend.background = element_blank(), # remove overall border
        #
        #the lower left corner of the legend is placed in the lower left corner of the drawing area
        legend.position=c(0,0),legend.justification = c(0,0))

Handling of maximum value

ybar

Having one value much higher than the others would be very empty on the right side.

So the author of the original graph made the y-axis fit most of the data, and then labeled the highest one bar with the actual data

#50
#set the axis range to a maximum of 50 to accommodate most data.
p<-p + coord_cartesian(ylim = c(-90,50)) + #y y-axis range, adjust according to actual condition
  # 
  #add data labels 
  geom_text(data = subset(df, score > 50),
            aes(index, 48,label=round(score))) + #50bar labeling of actual data on bar over 50
  geom_text(data = subset(df, index == 3),
            aes(index, score + 1,label = "*")) + # author's special marks
  geom_text(data = subset(df, index == nrow(df)),
            aes(index, score - 3, label = "T"))  # author's special marks
p

#PDF
#save to PDF file
ggsave("CancerBar_label.pdf",width = 8,height = 5)

Scenario 2Original

scorebar

Bars with score absolute values less than the threshold are displayed in gray.

IDscore

It contains two columns: ID and score

Start drawing

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(df,aes(x=index,y=score,fill=group)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity',width = 0.8) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("palegreen3","snow3","dodgerblue4")) + #bar color of bar
  scale_x_discrete(expand = expand_scale(add = .6)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(-30, 20, 5)) +
  coord_flip() + # coordinate axis interchange
  
  #2
  #draw 2 horizontal lines
  geom_hline(yintercept = c(-4,4), 
             color="white",
             linetype = 2,# draw a dotted line
             size = 0.3) + # thickness of line

  #label
  #write label
  geom_text(data = subset(df, score > 0),
            aes(x=index, y=-0.3, label=ID, color = group),#bar leave a gap between the bar and the axes
            size = 3, # font size
            hjust = "inward" ) +  #  the alignment of character
  geom_text(data = subset(df, score < 0),
            aes(x=index, y=0.3, label=ID, color = group),
            size = 3, hjust = "outward") +  
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("snow3","black","black")) +

  #
  #other themes
  labs(x = "", y = "t value of GSVA score, tumor \n versus non-malignant", 
       title = "Endothelial cells, tumour versus non-malignant") +
  theme_bw() + # remove background color
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + # remove gridlines
  theme(panel.border = element_rect(size = 0.6)) + # border thickness
  theme(axis.line.y = element_blank(), axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank()) + #y remove y-axis

  guides(fill=FALSE,color=FALSE) # legend not displayed
## Warning: The `size` argument of `element_rect()` is deprecated as of ggplot2 3.4.0.

Scenario 2Display non-significant results in gray

pvalue>0.05bar

Bar with pvalue > 0.05 is shown in gray

Input data

IDscorepvalue

It contains three columns, ID, score and pvalue

df<-read.csv("easy_input3.csv")
head(df)

## 6 leukocyte cell-cell adhesion 0.06715065  5.6860228
#pvalue
#grouped by pvalue
df$p.group<-cut(df$pval, breaks = c(-Inf,0.05,Inf),labels = c(1,0))
#score
#grouped by score
df$s.group<-cut(df$score, breaks = c(-Inf,0,Inf),labels = c(0,1))
#
#merge
df$ps.group <- paste0(df$p.group,df$s.group)

#pvaluescore3
#divided into 3 groups based on pvalue and score
df$group <- ifelse(df$ps.group=='10','1',ifelse(df$ps.group=='11','2','3'))

Start drawing

Only adjust the color order, the rest of the drawing code is the same as Scenario 2Original.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(df,aes(x=index,y=score,fill=group)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity',width = 0.8) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("palegreen3","dodgerblue4","snow3")) + # color
  scale_x_discrete(expand = expand_scale(add = .6)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(-30, 20, 5)) +
  coord_flip() + 
  
  geom_hline(yintercept = c(-4,4), 
             color="white",
             linetype = 2,
             size = 0.3) + 

  geom_text(data = subset(df, score > 0),
            aes(x=index, y=-0.3, label=ID, color = p.group),
            size=3,
            hjust = "inward") + 
  geom_text(data = subset(df, score < 0),
            aes(x=index, y=0.3, label=ID, color = p.group),
            size=3,hjust = "outward") +  
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("black","snow3")) +

  labs(x = "", y = "t value of GSVA score, tumor \n versus non-malignant", 
       title = "Endothelial cells, tumour versus non-malignant") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + 
  theme(panel.border = element_rect(size = 0.6)) + 
  theme(axis.line.y = element_blank(), axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank()) + 
  guides(fill=FALSE,color=FALSE)
